<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[150,1437,1245,2031]" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,501,1384,1408]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" reason="1">Diagnosis and description.</emphasis>
Forewing lengths of 
<quantity box="[734,849,1384,1407]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="16.0">16–17 mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[904,972,1384,1407]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="15.0">15mm</quantity>
for the male and female, respectively. The forewing differs from all other Palearctic congeners being the noctuid maculation lighter reddish-brown, than the ground color and forewing pattern differs by the lower parts of the orbicular and reniform stigmata confluent on the main vein forming a characteristic broad V. The forewing is more similar to four North American specie 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1154,1164,1488,1512]" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">s</emphasis>
(
<taxonomicName authority="Grote, 1874" authorityName="Grote" authorityYear="1874" box="[1180,1432,1488,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornuta">
<emphasis box="[1180,1295,1488,1511]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C. cornuta</emphasis>
Grote, 1874
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Lafontaine &amp; Crabo, 1997" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Crabo" authorityYear="1997" box="[151,582,1523,1546]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis box="[151,292,1523,1546]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C. robertsoni</emphasis>
Lafontaine &amp; Crabo, 1997
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Lafontaine &amp; Crabo, 1997" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Crabo" authorityYear="1997" box="[593,1032,1523,1546]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="enigmatica">
<emphasis box="[593,611,1523,1546]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[624,743,1523,1546]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">enigmatica</emphasis>
Lafontaine &amp; Crabo, 1997
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lafontaine &amp; Crabo, 1997" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Crabo" authorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis box="[1088,1106,1523,1546]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1119,1208,1523,1546]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">gloriosa</emphasis>
Lafontaine &amp; Crabo, 1997
</taxonomicName>
) but can be distinguished by the shape of the crosslines. Compared to the Neartic taxa (
<bibRefCitation author="Lafontaine" box="[1144,1330,1557,1580]" firstAuthor="Lafontaine" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" refId="ref3830" refString="Lafontaine, J. D. (1998) The Moths of America North of Mexico - 27.3 Noctuoidea, Noctuidae (part.). The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation." type="book" year="1998">Lafontaine, 1998</bibRefCitation>
) the male of the new taxon has narrower valvae terminally, a simple non-twisted vesica without subbasal cornutus, and a twin terminal cornutus. In the female genitalia the appendix bursae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gyulai, Ronkay &amp; Saldaitis" authorityYear="2011" box="[871,973,1627,1650]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspira">
<emphasis box="[871,973,1627,1650]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C. aspira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is simple (not coiled) and is considerably smaller than in the four Nearctic species; the shape and sclerotization of ostium bursae is different and the otherwise longer ductus bursae has different sclerotized parts. These genitalic differences also apply to the Palaearctic species, however similarities with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schiffermuller" authorityYear="1775" box="[428,593,1731,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucographa">
<emphasis box="[428,593,1731,1754]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C. leucographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
([Denis &amp; Schiffermüller], 1775) including tubular, helicoidally twisted vesica and the lack of a subbasal cornutus indicate a possible grouping with that species. Recent faunistic lists still include 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schiffermuller" authorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucographa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C. leucographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Ochsenheimer, 1816" authorityName="Ochsenheimer" authorityYear="1816" box="[448,773,1800,1823]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[448,537,1800,1823]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Cerastis</emphasis>
Ochsenheimer, 1816
</taxonomicName>
but suggestions to put it into a distinct genus began with Heinemann (1859), who established the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[666,716,1835,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Sora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[666,716,1835,1858]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Sora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Denis &amp; Schiffermuller" authorityYear="1775" box="[766,988,1835,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Noctua" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucographa">
<emphasis box="[766,988,1835,1858]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Noctua leucographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, suggested it was distinct. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tams" box="[151,288,1869,1892]" firstAuthor="Tams" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" pagination="135" refId="ref3901" refString="Tams, W. H. T. (1939) Gypsitea. Entomologist, 72, 135." type="journal article" year="1939">Tams (1939)</bibRefCitation>
stated the homonymy of 
<taxonomicName box="[571,621,1870,1893]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Sora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[571,621,1870,1893]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Sora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and gave the replacement name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tams" authorityYear="1939" box="[984,1079,1870,1893]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gypsitea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[984,1079,1870,1893]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Gypsitea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Nye" box="[1140,1256,1869,1892]" firstAuthor="Nye" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" refId="ref3862" refString="Nye, I. W. B. (1975) The Generic Names of the Moths of the World. Vol. 1. Noctuoidea. British Museum (Natural History). London, 568 pp." type="book" year="1975">Nye, 1975</bibRefCitation>
), and both 
<bibRefCitation author="Beck" firstAuthor="Beck" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" pagination="175 - 232" refId="ref3472" refString="Beck, H. (1992) Taxonomische Anderungen bei den Noctuinae, Cuculliinae und Plusiinae. Atalanta, 22, 175 - 232." type="journal article" year="1992">Beck (1992)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Fibiger" box="[275,431,1904,1927]" firstAuthor="Fibiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 848" refId="ref3568" refString="Fibiger, M. (1997) Noctuidae Europaeae. Volume 3. Noctuinae 3. Entomological Press, Soro. Heinemann, H. (1859): Die Schmetterlinge Deutschlands und der Schweiz: I - XXIII, 1 - 848. Braunschweig. Hemming, F., 1932." type="journal article" year="1997">Fibiger (1997)</bibRefCitation>
considered the possibility of a new taxon. There are clear male genitalic differences between the two allied species: the vesica of the new taxon is not twisted and bears two much shorter and wider basally coincident terminal cornuti, the terminal part of the valva is elongated, the basal part of the harpe is broader, distally thorn-like and dorsally curved, the juxta is differently shaped, and the medial incision is broadly U-formed.
</paragraph>
